"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:1.1.7\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">1.1.7</span> Sheaf</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">אֲלֻמָּה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(’alumah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen37:7\">GEN 37:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen37:7\">GEN 37:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen37:7\">GEN 37:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Gen37:7\">GEN 37:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps126:6\">PSA 126:6</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">עָמִיר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(‘amir)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer9:21\">JER 9:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos2:13\">AMO 2:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mic4:12\">MIC 4:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech12:6\">ZEC 12:6</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">עמר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(‘imer (verb))</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps129:7\">PSA 129:7</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">עֹמֶר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(‘omer)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:12\">LEV 23:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev23:15\">LEV 23:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Deut24:19\">DEU 24:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ruth2:7\">RUT 2:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ruth2:15\">RUT 2:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job24:10\">JOB 24:10</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">δράγμα</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(dragma)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt8:3\">JDT 8:3</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0934_sheaf.jpg\" alt=\"Sheaves of grain from the harvest\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Sheaves of grain from the harvest ( Jakub Hałun © Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>The sheaf was a bundle made by binding together the stalks and ears of a crop that had been harvested. The binding was most often done with stalks of the grain itself.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>Grain was harvested by cutting the stalks low to the ground with a sickle (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.1.6 Sickle&lt;REALIA:1.1.6&gt;</a>) or even by pulling them up by hand. The stalks were then gathered into bundles and tied together around the middle, making a sheaf. If the sheaves were not collected immediately, they could be left in the field in a standing position to keep the heads of grain off the damp ground. After the sheaves were collected, they were taken to the threshing floor (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">1.1.8.1 Threshing floor&lt;REALIA:1.1.8.1&gt;</a>).</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>For the word “sheaf,” translators may use a descriptive phrase, such as “bundle of harvested grain.” In some cultures the practice of tying grain into bundles is unknown. Some languages may have to say something like “bunch of grain you tie together.” In some cases it will be necessary to specify what kind of grain is involved. It may be possible to render “sheaf” in a more general sense as “harvest” (so <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps126:6\">PSA 126:6</a>; compare <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Job24:10\">JOB 24:10</a>, where it has “wheat”) or even “grain” (so <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> in <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos2:13\">AMO 2:13</a> and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mic4:12\">MIC 4:12</a>). Another passage where <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> renders “sheaf” in a broader sense is <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt8:3\">JDT 8:3</a>. The literal <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr> text has “as he stood overseeing the men who were binding sheaves in the field,” but <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr> says “while in the fields supervising the farm workers.”</p>\n<p>The Hebrew words <em>‘amir</em> and <em>‘omer</em> actually indicate a heap of many sheaves gathered at the edge of the field before being transported to the threshing floor, so the focus of <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Amos2:13\">AMO 2:13</a> is on the collective weight of the grain.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
